-- 
Crude Oil Volatility Falls as Futures Advance for a Third Day

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-08-29T21:23:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-29/crude-oil-volatility-falls-as-futures-advance-for-third-day.html
Oil options volatility decreased as
the underlying futures increased for a third day, climbing with
equities on optimism that the economy will expand and a report
that U.S. consumer spending gained in July.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 40.1 percent at 4 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 43.2 percent on Aug. 26.  Oil for October delivery increased $1.90, or 2.2 percent,
to settle at $87.27 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Prices have fallen 4.5 percent this year.  The most active contract in electronic trading today was
October $100 calls, with 2,063 lots changing hands. The options
rose 3 cents to 16 cents a barrel at 4:51 p.m. in New York.
October $92 calls, the next-most active option, gained 24 cents
to $1.07 with 1,632 lots trading. One contract covers 1,000
barrels of crude.  Calls outnumbered puts by 57 percent to 43 percent in
electronic trading on the Nymex.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occur the next business day.  October $80 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 3,970 lots changing hands. They fell 29
cents to $1.82 a barrel. The next-most active options, October
$75 puts, declined 21 cents to 95 cents a barrel on volume of
3,404.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
49,101 contracts. Next were December $70 puts with 43,993 and
December $80 puts with 42,849.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in Dallas at 
